o govern black players and prevent them from embracing styles and personas associated with blackness. This fascinating book discloses connections between the NBA's discourse and the broader discourse of antiblack racism. Particular policy changes that seemed aimed at black players, such as the NBA dress code and the debate over a minimum age requirement, are explored.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aAfrican American basketball players -- Social conditions. 0aAfrican American basketball playersxSocial conditions. 0aBasketball -- United States -- Sociological aspects. 0aBasketball fans -- United States -- Social conditions. 0aBasketball fanszUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 0aBasketballzUnited StatesxSociological aspects. 0aDiscrimination in sports -- United States. 0aDiscrimination in sportszUnited States. 0aMinorities in sports -- United States. 0aMinorities in sportszUnited States. 4aAfrican American Studies : African American Studies. 4aAmerican Studies : American Culture. 4aCriminology : Criminology. 4aSociology : Sociology. 4aSociology : Sports and Society. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Black Studies (Global).2bisacsh1 aCole, CL, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMessner, Michael A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143844207540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438442075423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438442075/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles